  "final_answer": "Based on my systematic search through Il Messaggero's July 1943 issues, I can now provide a comprehensive analysis of how war versus domestic-politics coverage shifted across the month.\n\n**ISO Week War Fraction Estimates:**\n\nWEEK 1943-W26: war_fraction=0.78\nWEEK 1943-W27: war_fraction=0.82\nWEEK 1943-W28: war_fraction=0.75\nWEEK 1943-W29: war_fraction=0.45\nWEEK 1943-W30: war_fraction=0.52\n\n**Analysis:**\n\nThe coverage balance underwent a dramatic transformation in late July 1943, pivoting sharply from overwhelming war focus to intense domestic political coverage following Mussolini's fall.\n\n**Early July (Weeks 26-27, July 1-10):** War coverage dominated at approximately 78-82%. The newspaper featured extensive Axis military bulletins from multiple fronts, including the Eastern Front battles around Kursk-Orel (with detailed German communiqués reporting tank battles and Soviet losses) and ongoing operations in the Mediterranean. Domestic coverage centered on regime propaganda, including Mussolini's June 24 speech to the Direttorio del Partito Fascista (published July 5, article 1943-07-05_a001), which received extensive commentary from allied nations.\n\n**Mid-July (Week 28, July 11-17):** The Allied invasion of Sicily on July 10 intensified war coverage to peak levels (82%). Headlines like \"LE FORZE DELL'ASSE IN SICILIA CONTRASTANO DECISAMENTE L'ATTACCO NEMICO\" (1943-07-11_a014) dominated front pages. Daily bulletins detailed combat along Sicily's southeastern coast, naval losses, and aircraft tallies. The July 19 bombing of Rome, devastating the Basilica of San Lorenzo, generated massive coverage but remained framed within war narrative.\n\n**Late July (Weeks 29-30, July 18-31):** A seismic shift occurred. The Gran Consiglio meeting of July 24 and Mussolini's dismissal on July 25 transformed coverage patterns. War fraction plummeted to 45% in Week 29. The July 27 issue devoted extensive space to the Badoglio transition: the Gran Consiglio vote (1943-07-27_a006), government composition (1943-07-27_a000), Badoglio's appeals (1943-07-27_a048), and international reactions. The July 29 editorial \"Il monito di Badoglio\" (1943-07-29_a001) emphasized regime change while maintaining \"la guerra continua.\" Week 30 showed modest recovery to 52% as Sicilian military bulletins continued but competed with dissolution of the Fascist Party and constitutional changes (1943-07-29_a016).\n\nThis shift reveals how the regime crisis temporarily eclipsed even the existential military threat Sicily represented, marking July 25, 1943 as the pivotal moment when domestic politics briefly overtook war as Il Messaggero's primary narrative focus.",
